But, on the matter of fact, Giraldus is egregiously mistaken'. Events which had occurred many centurias ago he brings near his own time, that the proximity might conveniently corroborate his false statement. This.is how the case really stands. It had three teeth of gold, one of which was given by Fiacha as wages to some men whom he had employed in erecting a bridge over the rivers Fersus and Menidamh; the other two were presented to the church to make a reliquary-case, on which the inhabitants of that country were aecustomed to purge or bind themselves by oath.
